+## Match the tool to the query shape — pick the lightest tool that answers it
+
+Classify the question FIRST; the right tool is the *lightest one that answers it*,
+not always \`omniweave_explore\`:
+
+- **Single-point — ONE symbol, ONE call:**
+    - need just its signature / kind / location (no body) → \`omniweave_search\` (the
+      lightest — don't spin up \`omniweave_explore\` to skim a signature off a bag of sources).
+    - need to SEE its source (body, constructor, overload) → ONE \`omniweave_node\`
+      (returns its location AND source) — \`omniweave_explore\` works too. Either is one call.
+  Don't chain two omniweave calls for one symbol; on a single literal locate a direct
+  grep/read also ties, so don't over-invest.
+- **Reverse / transitive / blast-radius / cross-boundary** — "what calls X?", "what
+  breaks if X changes?", "which step/script/method does this reach across a process or
+  language boundary?" → \`omniweave_callers\` / \`omniweave_impact\` / \`omniweave_explore\`.
+  THIS is where the graph pays for itself: grep would read O(call-sites) files and still
+  can't cross a subprocess or dynamic-dispatch boundary.
+- **Understand an area / "how does X work"** → ONE \`omniweave_explore\`.
